Bharat, Cairn, DLF, South Indian Bank: India Stocks Preview

-- B y   T u s h a r   D h a r a   a n d   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 
2011-07-01T03:13:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-01/bharat-cairn-dlf-south-indian-bank-india-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close, unless
otherwise stated.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
152.01, or 0.8 percent, to 18,845.87. The BSE 200 Index added
0.6 percent to 2,314.65. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on the National
Stock Exchange gained 0.8 percent to 5,647.40. SGX S&P CNX Nifty
Index futures for July delivery rose 0.8 percent to 5,698 as of
11:02 a.m. in  Singapore .  Bharat Petroleum Corp. (BPCL IN): India’s second-largest
state-run oil refiner is seeking to buy low-sulfur crude cargoes
of as much as 1 million barrels each for loading in the first
half of September, according to documents received by Bloomberg
News. The shares rose 1 percent to 650.25 rupees.  Cairn India Ltd. (CAIR)  : India’s largest aluminum maker
said Vedanta Resources Plc’s plan to take control of Cairn India
Ltd. was approved by India’s cabinet with conditions, Krishna
Tirath, minister for women and child development, said
yesterday. The shares rose 2.20 percent to 311.75 rupees.  DLF Ltd. (DLFU)  : India’s biggest developer will sell its
shareholding in the special economic zones of Pune, near Mumbai,
and Noida, near  New Delhi , for a combined value of 13 billion
rupees ($291 million) to cut its debt, the Economic Times
reported, without saying where it got the information.
Blackstone is likely to buy the special economic zones in Pune
for 9 billion rupees, the report said. DLF rose 0.7 percent to
210.45 rupees.  South Indian Bank Ltd. (SIB)  : The lender appointed three
advisers to manage a 10 billion-rupee share sale as it seeks to
double its business in the next three years, Chief Executive
Officer V.A. Joseph said yesterday. The shares rose 0.4 percent
to 24 rupees.  To contact the reporters on this story:
